content.description: Facing the POC go around right and down to see the start of this route.  A fingers traverse leads right, around the corner and up a steep crack.
content.protection: TR via bolts at the top of the POC

content.description:
Technical crimping/edging on superb, bullet hard rock, followed by a brilliant 90 degree arete.

The bottomless left arete is the obvious objective, and therein lies the problem, getting to the arete.  Start a couple feet left of Slap You Silly.  A hard pull on sharp crimps gives access to a left traverse across the face on patina edges.  From the large foot edge at the end of the traverse move up, then left to the obvious stance at the base of the arete.  From here one can finally do the stellar arete.

Long problem with sustained moves, feels more like a route than a bouldering problem.  The real problem isn't so much individual move difficulty as much as linking everything together.  The sharp holds have a tendancy to chew one up after a few tries.

The arete is superb.  To just do it by itself (maybe 12a), it's well worth pulling up past the edging to the stance at the base of it and going from there.

You kind of had to have been involved in the Woodson/Rubidoux skirmishes during the late 70's - early 90's to understand the name.
content.protection: Two bolt anchor at the top of the arete.
content.location: On the main face of the IMAX boulder.

content.description: Yet another very good thin right leaning tips crack.  Past the Poison Oak Crack at the left turning switchback on the right facing east, one can see the upper half of this route.  One of first 5.12s at Mt. Woodson
Desperate smearing and slapping your way up the blunt arete.  Use tricky smears and slopers to "bear hug" your way up.  Feels like an OW to climb.
content.protection: Two TR bolts up top.  Walk on and off via the west side of the boulder.
content.location: Directly across the road from the Big Grunt chimney.  On the Northeast side of the boulder.

content.description: Stay right for the left hand/foot match.  Easier problems exhist staying/starting left.
content.location: Just below the aid line on Hollywood boulder

content.description: This popular and moderate off width is a fun climb. The crux comes toward the bottom of the climb were the off width is a little akward. As you get higher the crack narrows and the angle backs off.
content.protection: Number 4 near the bottom, #1 as you get higher. Bolt anchor and rap rings at top of route.

content.description: Short crack with a very overhanging start and a big reach.  Tape gloves are helpful with the upper off-hands section.  You will have a lot of weight on your arms on this one.
content.protection: Small to medium cams and a medium nut to lead.  Can be top roped with medium cams.  I have to admit to bailing on my lead so look at it and take what looks good to you.
content.location: On a rock just past the Big Grunt chimney, on the left side of the road.  Can be seen from the road.  To set a TR continue past it up the next switchback and walk on top.

content.description: A nice boulder on excellent rock. Start in the jug layback flake, move up to the horizontal edge and mantle.
content.location: To the right of Monkey Crack, right off the road.

content.description:
On the south face of the Big Grunt boulder.  This route traverses up the obvious horizontal ramp.  Clip the first two bolts of Cool Jerk then traverse out right following the bolt line.  Crux comes at the third bolt which is hard to clip.  IMO, PG-13 for the awkward clips with potential for a swinging falls.  Pull powerful, then thin moves to the rings.

This is a longer route than most on Woodson so make sure you have a rope that is long enough.  Not your "Woodson rope."
content.protection:
Bolts and Draws

A double bolt anchor was recently replaced with rap rings by ASCA.
content.location: On the south face of the Big Grunt boulder.  Next to Hairdo and Cool Jerk.  Rap the route from the rings.  Someone might have to follow in order to retrieve the draws.

content.description: On the left side of the road across from the Poison Oak Crack, one will see a giant boulder with a couple of steep sport routes on the face.  The boulder itself is split into two via a superwide crack known as Big Grunt.   This route uses the the first two bolts of Cool Jerk and swings right then up.
Stand start with right hand on crimp and left on low sidepull/undercling, climb up to the dish then to crimps above it, dyno or reach to the top, easy mantel.
content.location: When hiking up hill on the road and passing cool jerk head to the next turn in the road (left turn)when standing near the edge of the turn look down hill there will be a long and large slab, at about two hunderd feet down you'll see a boulder by itself on top with some oak trees on the back side of it. The east side of the boulder is the climb.

content.description: This outstanding route is on the right hand side of the road, past Poison Oak Crack and the large square aid bolder.  Starting via cheatstones, there is a 10+ barndoor entry move to a few slightly easier moves, then a series of hard sequential moves up the orange water streak to finish.  Highly recommended
content.protection: Scramble up the side facing the road to TR bolts.  One may opt to wear climbing shoes to reach the bolts.

content.description: Overhanging seam. It climbs better than appearances suggest.
content.location: Located below Baby Edge and Hamburger Crack.

content.description: Start under a mini flake/roof (3") and edge, smear and crimp your way up the face.
content.protection: Two anchor bolts for a TR
content.location: Boulder is directly across the street from the Big Grunt Chimney.  Route is on the north face.  To the right of the "Slap you Silly" arete.

content.protection: Unless you've got a 15" cam or are sawing 2x4s to size on your way up, chimney technique IS your protection
content.location: Large crack right of Elsa's Crack

content.description: Perfect tight hand crack on not too steep rock.  The crux is the start as it's the narrowest jamming / steepest.  Still a very moderate climb.  Beautiful intro to hand jamming.
content.protection: Solo or cams.  Camalots #0.5-#1.  #1-3 for the anchor.  Very comfortable solo, but landing is pretty treacherous.
content.location: Head uphill on a low angle slab from the bend in the road just uphill from the Poison Oak Crack.  Can be seen from the road.

content.description: Climb the two scoops.

Do the opening moves of the standard Deport Jonny problem.  Instead of moving a little left from the flake, go right a couple of moves and proceed more or less straight up from there.  Sharp crimps and a couple of cool side-pull moves. At the top, refrain from joining the regular problem (not forced to do so) for a problem that is completely independent except for the opening couple of moves.   Good problem.

It is also possible to go straight up from the top of the opening flake.  This is almost like a third problem, and just like where it lies it is also rating wise (11+) between the other two.
content.protection: Use the same anchor as for Deport Jonny.

content.description: This face route is on the righthand side of the road immediately past the Poison Oak Crack behind the oak trees.     The route faces south and starts with a right leaning rail.  Crux comes near the top.

On the left side of the road across from the Poison Oak Crack, one will see a giant boulder with a couple of steep sport routes on the face. The boulder itself is split into two via a superwide crack known as Big Grunt.  This sport route runs up the center of this steep and super thin south face.

Start the climb on the obvious cheat stone start.  Try not to knock any blocks off.  Reach up into the underclings and pull on.  Traverse right using strength or trickery, lie back and stand up to an awkward rest.  Next, bust out across the glass face using the seam (crux), use the broken section above the seam to head straight up or continue across the seam to escape out right.
content.location: Directly across the road from Hamburger Crack. Walk on top of the huge boulder that caps the huge chimney below.  Set up the anchor on the south east side of the boulder down the smooth south east face.    Walk down on the south side of the boulder to find the start.  Look for the obvious cheat stone start.

content.description: Stand start at undercling, move more or less directly up face on sidepulls and crimps. Mantle
content.location: On the same boulder as "golden medallion", left side of face. See that problem for location directions.

content.description: Overhung start/offwidth! similar to big grunt, but shorter and has an awkward constriction, which mixes it up, requires some different techniques. Fun and worth a burn. Sit start for more of a challenge.
content.location: Located behind elsa's, up the hill. top out and walk off.

content.description: Big Grunt starts at the bottom of the obvious split in this large boulder (foreground) which sits atop Lunch Rock. A squeeze chimney start leads you to easier chimneying and eventually to the top.
